  1. Diamonds with fair cut tend to have largest carat. And diamonds with ideal cut tend to have smallest carat. In general, the better the cut is, the smaller the carat of the diamond tend to be.
ggplot(diamonds, aes(cut,carat)) + geom_boxplot()

c. This is because the larger the diamond is, the higher price it tends to have. And diamonds with worse cut usually have larger carat. Therefore, it appears that fair is nearly the best cut of diamond and ideal the worst cut.

  1. The first operartion: r could extract a column for dataframes by partial column name, however, r cannot do that for tibbles. The second operation: As for dataframes, r returns a vector instead of a dataframe when we ask for subsetting one column. And for tibbles, r returns a tibble when we ask for subsetting one column. The third operation: As for dataframes, r returns a dataframe when we ask for subsetting more than one columns. And for tibbles, r returns a tibble

4.2 Institutional Research

  1. Five examples of services that home health agencies: skilled nursing, physical therapy, occupational therapy, speech therapy and home health aide.

  2. An HHRG code is a code identifying to which Home Health Resource Group a patient belongs.Home Health Resource Groups divides patients into different groups based on the number of their therapy visits, their clinical levels, functional levels and their timing of visit.

  3. A HCC score evaluates whether a patient, compared to the overall average for the entire Medicare population, will cause a higher or lower spending of Medicare. A patient with a higher HCC score is expected to cause more spending and if the HCC score is higher than 1.08, the patient is expected to cause a higher spending than the average and vice versa.
    A patient with a HCC score of 0.75 will probably cost the Medicare much less than the average level of the entire Medicare population.
    A patient with a HCC score of 1.5 will probably cost the Medicare much more than average level of the entire Medicare population.

  4. A LUPA stands for “low utilization payment adjustment”, which means if a patient uses the home health agency service very few times (he or she visits the home health agency four or fewer times in a 60-day episode), he or she will get one reimbursement for each visit respectively rather than get a total reimbursement for an episode in the usual situation.

  1. The numbers from provider and provider_hhrg do not align. The reason why they do not align may include the difference in methodology and that the column “Total Episodes” in provider_hhrg is only the total count of non-LUPA episodes while the provider dataset provides both the number of non LUPA and LUPA.
# total number of episodes in provider : 6534036
summarise(provider, nLUPA_epi = sum(`Total Episodes (non-LUPA)`, na.rm=TRUE), LUPA_epi=sum(`Total LUPA Episodes`,na.rm = TRUE), n_total=nLUPA_epi+LUPA_epi)
## # A tibble: 1 x 3
##   nLUPA_epi LUPA_epi n_total
##       <dbl>    <dbl>   <dbl>
## 1   5975644   558392 6534036
# total number of episodes in provider_hhrg : 4194441
summarise(provider_hhrg, n_total=sum(`Total Episodes`))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   n_total
##     <dbl>
## 1 4194441
  1. The two columns “Provider ID” and “HHRG” together uniquely identify any row in provider_hhrg. By concatenating these two columns, we can create a new column “unique ID” and there are 104920 distinct values in this column, which is exactly the number of rows in provider_hhrg.
provider_hhrg$unique_ID <- paste(provider_hhrg$`Provider ID`,provider_hhrg$HHRG)
summarise(provider_hhrg, n_distinct=n_distinct(unique_ID))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   n_distinct
##        <int>
## 1     104920
